There is a possibility of converting the word and character frequency variables using TFIDF, but it need not necessarily lead to better models. So both scenarios – with and without performing TFIDF have been evaluated for each model. TFIDF is done by taking the term frequency variables (first 54) and multiplying with the IDF = (1+log (total emails / emails containing term)).¶

In [79]:
import math as mt

def tfidf(column):
    nt = len([i for i in column if i > 0])
    if(nt==0):
        return column*0
    else:
        doc_nt = 1+mt.log10(float(len(column))/float(nt))
        return column*doc_nt

word_freq_tfidf = data.iloc[:,0:54].apply(tfidf,axis = 1)
#word_freq_tfidf.head(2)

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import itertools

# This function prints and plots the confusion matrix.Normalization can be applied by setting `normalize=True`.

def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes,
                          normalize=False,
                          title='Confusion matrix',
                          cmap=plt.cm.Blues):
    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)

    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        print("Normalized confusion matrix")
    else:
        print('Confusion matrix, without normalization')

    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, cm[i, j],
                 horizontalalignment="center",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.ylabel('Predicted label')
    plt.xlabel('True label')
    
def model_evaluation(model,features,target,class_names,cnf_normalize=False):
    
    # importing necessary libraries
    from sklearn.metrics import f1_score,matthews_corrcoef,cohen_kappa_score,roc_curve,roc_auc_score,auc
    
    predicted = cross_validation.cross_val_predict(model, features, target['Actual'], cv=10)
    
    scores = cross_val_score(model, features, target['Actual'], cv=10)
   
    #Accuracy
    # The mean score and the 95% confidence interval of the score estimate are hence given by:
    display(HTML('<br><b>Accuracy:</b>'))
    print("Accuracy: %0.2f (+/- %0.2f)" % (scores.mean(), scores.std() * 2))

    # Confusion matrix
    conf_mtrx_dt = confusion_matrix(target['Actual'], predicted)

    plt.figure()
    plot_confusion_matrix(conf_mtrx_dt, classes=class_names,normalize=cnf_normalize,\
                          title='Confusion matrix')
    plt.show()
    display(HTML('<br><b>Confusion Matrix</b>'))
    display(pd.crosstab(predicted,target['Actual']))
    
    #Classification report
    display(HTML('<br><b>Classification Report</b>'))
    print metrics.classification_report(target['Actual'], predicted)
    
    # F measure
    display(HTML('<br><b>F Measure</b>'))
    print(f1_score(target['Actual'], predicted, average='binary'))
    
    # kappa statistic
    display(HTML('<br><b>Kappa Score</b>'))
    print(cohen_kappa_score(target['Actual'], predicted))
    
    # Matthews Correlation Coefficient 
    display(HTML('<br><b> Matthews correlation coefficient</b>'))
    print(matthews_corrcoef(target['Actual'], predicted))

Part 2: Misclassification Cost¶

We define a scorer function to eable us to judge a model based on misclassification cost¶

Evaluation metrics¶

In [74]:
from sklearn.metrics import make_scorer

def my_scorer_function(y_test, y_predicted):
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_predicted)
    return float(cm[0][1]*10 + cm[1][0]*1)/(cm[0][0] + cm[0][1] + cm[1][0] + cm[1][1])
